    "body": "I want to create an event handler which fires as soon as a message is received. I want the script to keep running indefinitely, listening for incoming messages. However, when I tested it, the event fires for the first few seconds after starting the script and any messages sent afterwards don't have any effect until I run the script again. What could be the problem? Could it be because of somewhat unstable wifi?\r\n\r\nHere's my code:\r\n\r\n```php\r\n<?php\r\n//set_time_limit(10);\r\nrequire_once '../src/whatsprot.class.php';\r\ndate_default_timezone_set('Asia/Calcutta');\r\n\r\n\r\n// phone number, deviceIdentity, and name.\r\n$options = getopt(\"d::\", array(\"debug::\"));\r\n$debug = (array_key_exists(\"debug\", $options) || array_key_exists(\"d\", $options)) ? true : false;\r\n\r\n\r\n// CONFIG\r\n$username = \"NNNNNNNNN\";\r\n$password = \"XXXXXXXXX\";\r\n$identity = \"XXXXXXXXX\";\r\n$nickname = \"XXXXXXXX\";\r\n$target = \"NNNNNNNNNN\";\r\n$debug = false;\r\n\r\nfunction onGetMessageCallback ($mynumber, $from, $id, $type, $time, $name, $body) {\r\n\techo \"From: $from\\tName: $name\\nBody: $body\\n\";\r\n}\r\n\r\necho \"[ ] Logging in....\\n\\n\";\r\n\r\n$w = new WhatsProt($username, $identity, $nickname, $debug);\r\n\r\n$w->eventManager()->bind(\"onGetMessage\", \"onGetMessageCallback\");\r\n\r\n$w->connect();\r\n\r\n$w->loginWithPassword($password);\r\n\r\necho \"[*] Connected to WhatsApp\\n\\n\";\r\n\r\n\r\nwhile(1)\r\n{\r\n    $w->PollMessage();\r\n    sleep(1);\r\n }\r\n\r\n?>\r\n```",
